{"id":"10.1103/PhysRevFluids.1.083302","title":{"value":"Interplay between viscosity and elasticity in freely expanding liquid sheets","format":"html+mathml"},"publisher":{"name":"APS"},"journal":{"id":"PRFLUIDS","abbreviatedName":"Phys. Rev. Fluids","name":"Physical Review Fluids"},"issue":{"number":"8"},"volume":{"number":"1"},"pageStart":"083302","hasArticleId":true,"date":"2016-12-16","numPages":15,"articleType":"article","identifiers":{"doi":"10.1103/PhysRevFluids.1.083302"},"rights":{"rightsStatement":"©2016 American Physical Society","copyrightYear":2016,"copyrightHolders":[{"name":"American Physical Society"}]},"authors":[{"type":"Person","name":"Srishti Arora","firstname":"Srishti","surname":"Arora","affiliationIds":["a1"]},{"type":"Person","name":"Christian Ligoure","firstname":"Christian","surname":"Ligoure","affiliationIds":["a1"]},{"type":"Person","name":"Laurence Ramos","firstname":"Laurence","surname":"Ramos","affiliationIds":["a1"]}],"affiliations":[{"id":"a1","name":"Laboratoire Charles Coulomb, UMR No. 5221, CNRS, Université de Montpellier, F-34095 Montpellier, France"}],"abstract":{"value":"<p>We investigate the dynamics of freely expanding liquid sheets prepared with fluids with different rheological properties: (i) Viscous fluids with a zero-shear viscosity <span class=\"aps-inline-formula\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>η</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></math></span> in the range <span class=\"aps-inline-formula\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>–</mo><mn>1000</mn><mspace width=\"0.28em\"></mspace><mi>mPa</mi><mspace width=\"0.16em\"></mspace><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mrow></math></span> and (ii) viscoelastic fluids whose linear viscoelastic behavior in the frequency range <span class=\"aps-inline-formula\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mrow><mn>0.1</mn><mo>–</mo><mn>100</mn></mrow></math></span> rad/s can be accounted for by a Maxwell fluid model, whose characteristic elastic modulus <span class=\"aps-inline-formula\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>G</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></math></span>, relaxation time <span class=\"aps-inline-formula\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>τ</mi></math></span>, and zero-shear viscosity <span class=\"aps-inline-formula\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mrow><msub><mi>η</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>G</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mi>τ</mi></mrow></math></span>, can be tuned over several orders of magnitude. The sheets are produced by a drop of fluid impacting a small cylindrical solid target. For viscoelastic fluids, we show that, when <span class=\"aps-inline-formula\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>τ</mi></math></span> is shorter than the typical lifetime of the sheet (<span class=\"aps-inline-formula\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mrow><mo>∼</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow></math></span> ms), the dynamics of the sheet is similar to that of Newtonian viscous liquids with equal zero-shear viscosity. In that case, for little viscous samples (<span class=\"aps-inline-formula\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mrow><msub><mi>η</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>≲</mo><mn>30</mn></mrow></math></span> mPa s), the maximal expansion of the sheet <span class=\"aps-inline-formula\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>d</mi><mi>max</mi></msub></math></span> is independent of <span class=\"aps-inline-formula\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>η</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></math></span>, whereas for more viscous samples, <span class=\"aps-inline-formula\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>d</mi><mi>max</mi></msub></math></span> decreases as <span class=\"aps-inline-formula\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>η</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></math></span> increases. We provide a simple model for the dependence of the maximal expansion of the sheet with the viscosity that accounts well for our experimental data. By contrast, when <span class=\"aps-inline-formula\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>τ</mi></math></span> is longer than the typical lifetime of the sheet, the behavior drastically differs. The sheet expansion is strongly enhanced as compared to that of viscous samples with comparable zero-shear viscosity, but is heterogeneous with the occurrence of cracks, revealing the elastic nature of the viscoelastic fluid.</p>","format":"html+mathml"},"classificationSchemes":{"physh":{"disciplines":[{"id":"512fd433-7b6d-4535-bb60-78f3bf431bc3","label":"Fluid Dynamics"},{"id":"2bd35371-7fda-477a-8e1a-c346c797a232","label":"Polymers & Soft Matter"}],"concepts":[{"id":"3b61a8e0-cd86-40c6-a37c-c40381648f56","label":"Imaging","facet":{"id":"705f7ed8-5e20-47e1-8ca4-fa7feea8ad84","label":"Experimental Techniques"},"primary":true},{"id":"109568d814844bfba6b47be793954e65","label":"Oscillatory measurements","facet":{"id":"705f7ed8-5e20-47e1-8ca4-fa7feea8ad84","label":"Experimental Techniques"}},{"id":"8939314c-888d-47be-9fc8-d481ef4879d4","label":"Free-surface flows","facet":{"id":"bdb1ef91-b776-4e36-8f8f-3e93666bac1e","label":"Research Areas"}},{"id":"8f585b75-23e9-4388-afe5-364824c412da","label":"Surface tension effects","facet":{"id":"f45b3c40-959c-4e90-ba0e-38232980802a","label":"Physical Systems"}},{"id":"1f72b9f10dd7454f861d6c5927dfb128","label":"Micelles","facet":{"id":"f45b3c40-959c-4e90-ba0e-38232980802a","label":"Physical Systems"}},{"id":"1c31e6d2dd5b4e16995aa4a7f659f9c5","label":"Hydrogels","facet":{"id":"f45b3c40-959c-4e90-ba0e-38232980802a","label":"Physical Systems"}},{"id":"1761a12d-b815-4d04-96f8-de6a32f98320","label":"Drops of complex fluids","facet":{"id":"f45b3c40-959c-4e90-ba0e-38232980802a","label":"Physical Systems"}},{"id":"b14c11c6-6e81-44c1-a1ff-2ec4d1a95359","label":"Non-Newtonian fluids","facet":{"id":"bdb1ef91-b776-4e36-8f8f-3e93666bac1e","label":"Research Areas"}},{"id":"8c304260-0dba-4a63-908f-bab534c0a876","label":"Viscoelasticity","facet":{"id":"bdb1ef91-b776-4e36-8f8f-3e93666bac1e","label":"Research Areas"}},{"id":"36c186b3-6f92-4d27-a215-e59d74aa95b6","label":"Interfacial phenomena","facet":{"id":"bdb1ef91-b776-4e36-8f8f-3e93666bac1e","label":"Research Areas"}},{"id":"52399a41-c27b-49c2-96c3-120524795d0b","label":"Complex fluids","facet":{"id":"bdb1ef91-b776-4e36-8f8f-3e93666bac1e","label":"Research Areas"}}]}}}